<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence by Simon Renwick</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Simon Renwick</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> (SCE0028)</span></a></h3><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The purpose of this submission is to address one of the questions posed by the Liaison Committee, namely ‘What more can be done?’ I shall argue that, contrary to previous inquiries, there should be strict penalty rules in place regarding attendance.  The submission shall be split into four sections:</span></li></ol><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Select Committee Importance and the Wright Reforms to Select Committees</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rebuttals and recommendations to ‘problems’ with an attendance rule</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A recommendation for a penalisation system</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 77pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Concluding Remarks</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">The importance of the Select Committee Process &amp; The Wright Reforms</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Firstly though, the fundamental importance of the select committee system must be outlined. As Kelly and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Suchenia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> note, the core tasks of select committees include the examination of policy proposals, departmental expenditure and thorough scrutiny on governmental activity</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. As well as this, the Liaison Committee has previously stated that the committee system allows MPs to wield influence over the government</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clearly, select committees have the ability to influence the government in spheres of activity that influence is highly lucrative in; as well, the scrutiny the select committee conducts is on highly important areas of government activity.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is why committee effectiveness is crucial; select committees are a clear and effective check on the executive outside of the legislative chamber, whether it is the Liaison Committee’s bi-annual questioning of the PM, or the Education Committee</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">using their power to ask Michael Gove questions from the Twitter search ‘#</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">AskGove</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. A healthy democratic political process requires an effective committee system, to act as a means of accounting for government activity on a specific issue or area. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When looking at current attendance rules, the Wright reforms must be examined. The Wright Committee proposed a wave of new procedures, practices and culture for select committees, and these reforms have been recognised, by both select committees themselves and the Coalition Government, to have had an impact and created progress in the region of select committee effectiveness</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One of the key Wright Committee reforms was the implementation of a quasi-60% attendance requirement of MPs to their select committee, and such a point was furthered in evidence given on the inquiry</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. As said by the Wright Committee:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“Any member of a select committee whose cumulative attendance during a Session is below 60% should be automatically discharged at the end of that Session”</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, following committees have noted several potential concerns with attendance rules</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The following section will argue why in fact stricter rules on committee attendance will be beneficial, not a hindrance.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Attendance generally above 60%</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The first critique of a 60% attendance rule was that it’s simply unnecessary; there are few incidents of MPs registering less than 60% committee attendance over a term</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However this merely means attendance is above 60%, and there is not real justification for this level of attendance</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Despite this figure including MPs absence and times when MPs cannot make meetings (as shall be discussed later), there are no rules for MPs to have to produce work if they miss these meetings. Therefore, a 60% attendance record means the standard set by Parliament is that an MP can miss four of every ten meeting with no contribution to the process, and not be penalised.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">My first recommendation is that attendance to select committee meetings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be 100% without reasonable absence (and even then procedure should be put in place to make MPs contribute); levels of participation would be at the highest possible level, more members would be involved in debating/report-crafting, and in no way could be harmful to the process of scrutiny. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Previous concerns can be alleviated simply by raising the standards we set for our MPs with regards to select committees; we shouldn’t expect only ‘adequate’ standards of MPs, we should only expect the best from those who are directly holding our government and state </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to account, and this is especially apt when discussing select committee involvement as it is clearly an incredibly important sphere of scrutiny on government activity.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Legitimate Absence</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There must be recognition however, that MPs sometimes cannot make committee meetings, despite their best intentions. Whether because of family illness or committee clashes which means prioritisation of one committee over another, MPs will undoubtedly at some point in their tenure be faced with a scenario whereby they simply cannot attend a meeting.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is understandable; some MPs live hundreds of miles away from Westminster, making attendance of quickly scheduled meetings in London impossible. As well, some MPs will obviously be affected by illness at some point of their term, or have a close family member who is. An MP may simply be on several committees, who may meet at the same time one week.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The second recommendation is that, when scenarios like this occur, MPs still have a duty to contribute to the select committee process. The recommendation follows that clerks will record select committee meetings using a Dictaphone.  An .mp3 file can then be uploaded to a secure database in Parliament, and the file can be distributed to any member that missed the meeting.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MP must then listen through the committee meeting and make notes on the meeting, regarding their opinions on the matter and recommendations if required. The Clerk should then add this to the document or papers that are to be distributed at the next committee meeting. These measures are simple and do not require great effort on the behalf of the MP or clerk.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> These measures will also help MPs that are unable to attend meetings to still have an opinion expressed on given issues despite their absence. It will certainly not hamper the process of select committee effectiveness, and will most certainly help the process through</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more scrutiny on a subject, which leads to more thorough assessment of the inquiry. As well, it will allow for more opinions to be voiced.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If an MP fails to do this it will count as a misdemeanour, and this only doesn’t apply when the MP is physically unable to do the work due to serious illness/ injury.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Recommended Penalty System as a form of incentive to attend</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The only obstacle hampering these recommendations is currently no method to incentivise MPs to follow such rules; the only mild incentive for MPs to attend is that a meeting is void if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">less than a quarter or three members attend</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well, despite the Wright reforms meaning that chairs can request a debate to be held on an MP’s involvement in a select committee if attendance drops below 60%</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, there is still the ‘problem’ of MPs not attending purely because they don’t want to participate in the committee</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; the Wright reforms do not stop this problem from occurring.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">But MPs cannot simply disregard a form of scrutiny due to their dislike of the subject – select committees are vital to the democratic process and so if an MP is made to participate in a committee’s activity they should to the best of their ability attend and participate. Therefore, a way to prevent ‘coasting’, or simply negligent behaviour towards select committees, from MPs who hope to be removed from a committee, and for any MP who fails to follow the aforementioned recommendation, should be subject to penalisation past committee membership.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The penalty system would work on two levels; monetary and political, and applies if a given MP has not either attended a meeting/debate without good reason, or has failed to fulfil the requirements of absence from a meeting. After three warnings, penalisation would apply for every misdemeanour following in the given term.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This notion of the monetary aspect is simple;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPs are currently paid £66,396</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including benefits. Simply, if they do not carry out one of their most important tasks as an MP, why should they be paid their full salary? The severity of such a cut would be subject to debate, but the simple idea of monetary disciplining would surely stop some MPs from not attending or contributing.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There must be a recognition though that some MPs have enough money that minor salary cuts wouldn’t have the desired affect; for instance in 2012 it was reported 18 out of 29 Government ministers were millionaires</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; the likelihood there are scarce more in Parliament outside the cabinet would be benign. This means there must </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> other methods of penalisation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Political ramification should apply as well, and these could include:</span></li><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 140pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Exclusion from Private Members Bill selection</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 140pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Exclusion from debates/ Prime Ministers Questions/ Ministers Questions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol></ol></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPs enter Parliament to make a difference or to scrutinise the government; if they are prevented from doing this then they will look to eradicate any behaviour that leads to this; this will surely mean more MPs feeling incentivised to either attend all possible select committee meetings or contributing via post-meeting reports in their absence.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Concluding Remarks</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To conclude, the importance of select committee is evident. As well as this, the effectiveness of a select committee is clearly correlative to the input and effort made by its members. As this submission has made clear therefore, raising the standards of effort made in select committees can only be beneficial for the system, and Parliament.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The reforms would clearly put the earnest on MPs to carry out their role on a select committee no matter the obstacle, with practical and feasible alternatives if they cannot attend meetings which will increase contributions and therefore effectiveness. As well, the recommendations clearly incentivise MPs to carry out their role for fear of penalisation. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For anybody who believes the penalisations aren’t legitimate or aren’t fair, the complaint shouldn’t be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">centered</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the system, but more why the MP put themselves in such a position to be penalised.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In short, select committee effectiveness can be improved through simple and practical measures; these measures shouldn’t act as a strain on MPs time, as in theory MPs should attend all committee meetings anyway, and the tasks set for them as a result of absence from these meetings is certainly not far more strenuous than participating in a committee in the first place. As well, the implementation of such measures is logistically practical, and shouldn’t run up too high an expenditure – the only thing that will be increased is the Clerk’s requirements for select committee meetings and expenditure on recording devices.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Through all of these measures, it is clear that the select committee system can be reformed and furthered even more, and made to be an even more effective component of the Parliamentary system than it already is.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">20 December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Select Committee – Core Tasks, p.4</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Kelly, R. Effectiveness of Select Committee – p.4 </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9.5pt"> Parliament Website. (2012) ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9.5pt">Michael Gove answers #</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9.5pt">AskGove</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9.5pt"> twitter questions during Education Committee evidence session’, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9.5pt; font-style:italic">Education Select Committee News,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9.5pt"> </span><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/education-committee/news/secretary-of-state-ev-session/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9.5pt; te